The assignment operator can be overloaded to allow assignment to your class. If you do not provide an overloaded assignment operator, the compiler will create one for you. Overloaded assignment operators should always include a self-assignment check (unless it’s handled naturally, or you’re using the copy and swap idiom).New programmers often mix up when the assignment operator vs copy constructor are used, but it’s fairly straightforward:If a new object has to be created before the copying can occur, the copy constructor is used (note: this includes passing or returning objects by value).If a new object does not have to be created before the copying can occur, the assignment operator is used.By default, the copy constructor and assignment operators provided by the compiler do a memberwise initialization or assignment, which is a shallow copy. If your class dynamically allocates memory, this will likely lead to problems, as multiple objects will end up pointing to the same allocated memory. In this case, you’ll need to explicitly define these in order to do a deep copy. Even better, avoid doing your own memory management if you can and use classes from the standard library.Quiz timeQuestion #1AssumingPointis a class andpointis an instance of that class, should you use a normal/friend or member function overload for the following operators?a)point + pointShow Solutionbinaryoperator+is best implemented as a normal/friend function.b)-pointShow Solutionunaryoperator-is best implemented as a member function.c)std::cout << pointShow Solutionoperator<<must be implemented as a normal/friend function.d)point = 5;Show Solutionoperator=must be implemented as a member function.Question #2Write a class named Average that will keep track of the average of all integers passed to it. Use two members: The first one should be typestd::int32_t, and used to keep track of the sum of all the numbers you’ve seen so far. The second should keep track of how many numbers you’ve seen so far. You can divide them to find your average.a) Write all of the functions necessary for the following program to run:int main()
